>>94221878
>how manufactured was nirvana's rise to fame, i.e. was it truly a case of a subculture organically growing into something which caught the eye of the mainstream, or was it major label-supported from the start?
From everything I've seen, it was pretty organic. For instance, I recall seeing interviews where Mark Lanegan claimed that Sub Pop didn't see the potential in Nirvana and didn't expect them to get even remotely big. This is probably part of the reason why they switched labels to Geffen. It was likely expected that Nevermind would be successful, but not nearly to the extent that it was.
>how big were nirvana really at their prime?
Big, but probably not as big as most people think. They appealed mostly to a certain demographic and subculture, with only their huge singles being more universal.
